Port uu_chown 0.8.0 to a NATIVE in-process brush builtin. Unlike chmod, chown's
file iteration, diagnostics, and verbose output all live in uucore::perms
(shared with chgrp), so the logical-I/O seam lives there too:

* uucore::perms (vendor/uucore): a per-thread capture flag + PERMS_OUT/PERMS_ERR
  buffers, with crate-local show_error!/perms_out! macros that buffer while
  capture is ON and fall through to the real show_error!/println! (process fd
  1/2) while OFF. So non-chown callers (chmod uses get_metadata /
  configure_symlink_and_recursion / common_args; chgrp) and the standalone chown
  binary are byte-for-byte unchanged. New chown_base_io(... cwd, out, err)
  enables capture for executor.exec(), resolves relative file operands against
  the logical cwd, and drains the buffers to the injected sinks; chown_base
  (standalone) calls the shared impl with cwd=None.
* uu_chown (vendor/uu_chown): chown_main(args, cwd, out, err) routes through
  chown_base_io; the relative --reference RFILE is resolved via a thread-local
  CHOWN_CWD seam (the parser is a bare fn pointer, so cwd can't be threaded
  through its signature).

As a non-root caller chown(2) commonly fails EPERM — that diagnostic is surfaced
faithfully (GNU/uutils behavior). The #[uucore::main] uumain bridge is retained.

